      <data key="d5">1776197130</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Lifetime Episodes">
      <data key="d0">Lifetime Episodes</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">A person's lifetime episodes of major depressive disorder (MDD) refer to the recurring periods of major depression that a person experiences throughout their life.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-8b090779071c8e7710d56eea47326cc5</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776197131</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Distinct Episodes">
      <data key="d0">Distinct Episodes</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">A distinct episode of major depressive disorder (MDD) refers to a period during which the symptoms of major depression are present and severe enough to cause significant distress.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-8b090779071c8e7710d56eea47326cc5</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776197131</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Person's Lifetime">
      <data key="d0">Person's Lifetime</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">A person's lifetime refers to the duration of their existence, encompassing all periods from birth until death.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-8b090779071c8e7710d56eea47326cc5</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776197131</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Medication">
      <data key="d0">Medication</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-8b090779071c8e7710d56eea47326cc5</data>
      <data key="d2">Medication can be an integral part of the treatment protocol for dysthymia.</data>
      <data key="d1">UNKNOWN</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776197132</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Dysthymia and Psychotherapy">
      <data key="d0">Dysthymia and Psychotherapy</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-8b090779071c8e7710d56eea47326cc5</data>
      <data key="d2">Psychotherapy is a recognized therapeutic approach for addressing dysthymia.</data>
      <data key="d1">UNKNOWN</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776197132</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Psychotherapy method">
      <data key="d0">Psychotherapy method</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-8b090779071c8e7710d56eea47326cc5</data>
      <data key="d2">Psychotherapy is a recognized therapeutic approach for addressing dysthymia.</data>
      <data key="d1">UNKNOWN</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776197133</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Acrodermatitis Chronica Atrophicans">
      <data key="d0">Acrodermatitis Chronica Atrophicans</data>
      <data key="d1">data</data>
      <data key="d2">Acrodermatitis chronica atrophicans is a skin condition characterized by progressive inflammation and thickening of the skin.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-58ce513efff4e4279006c76309bbe13e</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776197726</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Tick Bite">
      <data key="d0">Tick Bite</data>
      <data key="d1">event</data>
      <data key="d2">A tick bite can trigger the development of acrodermatitis chronica atrophicans in some patients.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-58ce513efff4e4279006c76309bbe13e</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776197726</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Erythema Migrans">
      <data key="d0">Erythema Migrans</data>
      <data key="d1">symptom</data>
      <data key="d2">Erythema migrans is a skin symptom that may occur before or after the development of acrodermatitis chronica atrophicans.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-58ce513efff4e4279006c76309bbe13e</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776197726</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="693 Patients">
      <data key="d0">693 Patients</data>
      <data key="d1">data</data>
      <data key="d2">A study involving 693 patients with acrodermatica chronica atrophicans found that approximately 85% remembered a tick bite.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-58ce513efff4e4279006c76309bbe13e</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776197726</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Neurological Symptoms">
      <data key="d0">Neurological Symptoms</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-58ce513efff4e4279006c76309bbe13e</data>
      <data key="d2">Neurological symptoms are a common feature of acrodermatitis chronica atrophicans.</data>
      <data key="d1">UNKNOWN</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776197729</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Rheumatological Symptoms">
      <data key="d0">Rheumatological Symptoms</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-58ce513efff4e4279006c76309bbe13e</data>
      <data key="d2">Rheumatological symptoms also accompany acrodermatitis chronica atrophicans.</data>
      <data key="d1">UNKNOWN</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776197729</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Duration of Disease">
      <data key="d0">Duration of Disease</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-58ce513efff4e4279006c76309bbe13e</data>
      <data key="d2">The duration of the disease determines the severity and type of skin involvement in acrodermatitis chronica atrophicans.</data>
      <data key="d1">UNKNOWN</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776197730</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Extensor Surfaces">
      <data key="d0">Extensor Surfaces</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-58ce513efff4e4279006c76309bbe13e</data>
      <data key="d2">The extensor surfaces of limbs are commonly involved in acrodermatitis chronica atrophicans.</data>
      <data key="d1">UNKNOWN</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776197730</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Inflammatory Stage">
      <data key="d0">Inflammatory Stage</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-58ce513efff4e4279006c76309bbe13e</data>
      <data key="d2">The inflammatory stage is characterized by bluish-red discoloration and edema in the skin of patients with acrodermatitis chronica atrophicans.</data>
      <data key="d1">UNKNOWN</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776197731</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Atrophic Phase">
      <data key="d0">Atrophic Phase</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-58ce513efff4e4279006c76309bbe13e</data>
      <data key="d2">The atrophic phase involves thickening and hardening of the skin in patients with acrodermatitis chronica atrophicans.</data>
      <data key="d1">UNKNOWN</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776197731</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Sclerotic Skin Plaques">
      <data key="d0">Sclerotic Skin Plaques</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-58ce513efff4e4279006c76309bbe13e</data>
      <data key="d2">Sclerotic skin plaques may develop in patients with acrodermatitis chronica atrophicans.</data>
      <data key="d1">UNKNOWN</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776197732</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Peripheral Neuropathy">
      <data key="d0">Peripheral Neuropathy</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-58ce513efff4e4279006c76309bbe13e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-05a062c31232f7d983bd96c0052adfc7</data>
      <data key="d2">Peripheral neuropathy is a characteristic feature of acrodermatitis chronica atrophicans.&lt;SEP&gt;Peripheral neuropathy is a condition that affects the peripheral nerves and can cause various symptoms.</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776226350</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Paresthesia and Hypesthesia">
      <data key="d0">Paresthesia and Hypesthesia</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-58ce513efff4e4279006c76309bbe13e</data>
      <data key="d2">Paresthesia (numbness) and hypesthesia (tingling) are common symptoms of peripheral neuropathy in acrodermatitis chronica atrophicans.</data>
      <data key="d1">UNKNOWN</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776197733</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Symptoms at Lesion Site">
      <data key="d0">Symptoms at Lesion Site</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-58ce513efff4e4279006c76309bbe13e</data>
      <data key="d2">Symptoms such as paresthesia and hypesthesia may occur at the exact site of acrodermatitis chronica atrophicans's lesion in some patients.</data>
      <data key="d1">UNKNOWN</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776197734</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Symptoms at Other Sites">
      <data key="d0">Symptoms at Other Sites</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-58ce513efff4e4279006c76309bbe13e</data>
      <data key="d2">Symptoms such as paresthesia and hypesthesia may occur at other sites in patients with acrodermatitis chronica atrophicans.</data>
      <data key="d1">UNKNOWN</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776197734</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Asymmetric Distal Sensory Disturbance">
      <data key="d0">Asymmetric Distal Sensory Disturbance</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-58ce513efff4e4279006c76309bbe13e</data>
      <data key="d2">The symptom of asymmetric distal sensory disturbance can be painful or painless in patients with acrodermatitis chronica atrophicans.</data>
      <data key="d1">UNKNOWN</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776197735</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Constitutional Symptoms">
      <data key="d0">Constitutional Symptoms</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-58ce513efff4e4279006c76309bbe13e</data>
      <data key="d2">Constitutional symptoms such as fever and fatigue may accompany acrodermatitis chronica atrophicans.</data>
      <data key="d1">UNKNOWN</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776197736</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Fever and Fatigue">
      <data key="d0">Fever and Fatigue</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-58ce513efff4e4279006c76309bbe13e</data>
      <data key="d2">Fever and fatigue are common constitutional symptoms in patients with acrodermatitis chronica atrophicans.</data>
      <data key="d1">UNKNOWN</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776197736</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Lower Limb Involvement">
      <data key="d0">Lower Limb Involvement</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-58ce513efff4e4279006c76309bbe13e</data>
      <data key="d2">The lower limb is more commonly involved than the upper limb in acrodermatitis chronica atrophicans.</data>
      <data key="d1">UNKNOWN</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776197737</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Upper Limb Involvement">
      <data key="d0">Upper Limb Involvement</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-58ce513efff4e4279006c76309bbe13e</data>
      <data key="d2">The upper limb is less commonly involved than the lower limb in acrodermatitis chronica atrophicans.</data>
      <data key="d1">UNKNOWN</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776197737</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Bilateral Acral Involvement">
      <data key="d0">Bilateral Acral Involvement</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-58ce513efff4e4279006c76309bbe13e</data>
      <data key="d2">A significant proportion of patients with acrodermatitis chronica atrophicans experience bilateral acral involvement.</data>
      <data key="d1">UNKNOWN</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776197738</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Unilateral Skin Involvement">
      <data key="d0">Unilateral Skin Involvement</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-58ce513efff4e4279006c76309bbe13e</data>
      <data key="d2">Only a small fraction of patients with acrodermatitis chronica atrophicans have unilateral skin involvement.</data>
      <data key="d1">UNKNOWN</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776197739</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Nodule and Arthritis">
      <data key="d0">Nodule and Arthritis</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-58ce513efff4e4279006c76309bbe13e</data>
      <data key="d2">A small proportion of patients experience symptoms such as nodules, arthritis, itching, muscle atrophy, joint deformities, and paresis.</data>
      <data key="d1">UNKNOWN</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776197739</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Muscle Atrophy">
      <data key="d0">Muscle Atrophy</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-58ce513efff4e4279006c76309bbe13e</data>
      <data key="d2">Muscle atrophy is a rare symptom of acrodermatitis chronica atrophicans.</data>
      <data key="d1">UNKNOWN</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776197740</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Paresis">
      <data key="d0">Paresis</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-58ce513efff4e4279006c76309bbe13e</data>
      <data key="d2">Paresis (weakness) is a rare symptom associated with acrodermatitis chronica atrophicans.</data>
      <data key="d1">UNKNOWN</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776197740</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Edema and Atrophic Changes">
      <data key="d0">Edema and Atrophic Changes</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-58ce513efff4e4279006c76309bbe13e</data>
      <data key="d2">In some cases, the main presentation of acrodermatitis chronica atrophicans is edema (swelling) and atrophic changes.</data>
      <data key="d1">UNKNOWN</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776197741</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Knee Joint Effusion">
      <data key="d0">Knee Joint Effusion</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-58ce513efff4e4279006c76309bbe13e</data>
      <data key="d2">In some cases, patients with acrodermatitis chronica atrophicans may experience knee joint effusion (fluid accumulation in the joint).</data>
      <data key="d1">UNKNOWN</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776197741</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Personality Changes">
      <data key="d0">Personality Changes</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-58ce513efff4e4279006c76309bbe13e</data>
      <data key="d2">In some cases, patients with acrodermatitis chronica atrophicans may experience personality changes due to central nervous system involvement.</data>
      <data key="d1">UNKNOWN</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776197742</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Aortic Sinus">
      <data key="d0">Aortic Sinus</data>
      <data key="d1">location</data>
      <data key="d2">The aortic sinus is a section of the ascending aorta that is normally dilated just above the aortic valve.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-830f7c80bbd34b9d892fbd4d5954c36a</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776198947</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Ascending Aorta">
      <data key="d0">Ascending Aorta</data>
      <data key="d1">organ</data>
      <data key="d2">The ascending aorta is the part of the aorta immediately below the left ventricle, which pumps oxygenated blood to the body and head during fetal development.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-830f7c80bbd34b9d892fbd4d5954c36a</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776198947</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Aortic Valve">
      <data key="d0">Aortic Valve</data>
      <data key="d1">naturalobject</data>
      <data key="d2">Located at the junction between the left ventricle and the ascending aorta, the aortic valve regulates blood flow from the heart to the rest of the body.&lt;SEP&gt;The aortic valve regulates blood flow from the heart to the rest of the body.&lt;SEP&gt;The aortic valve is affected in aortic stenosis.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-830f7c80bbd34b9d892fbd4d5954c36a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-edfc413f95838bcb6bb18546eedcab43&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c5d390cb21e6dd1e2d80ae8661e921a2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ea34669e3dc11beced307b643d8c67a4</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776234585</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Left Aortic Sinus">
      <data key="d0">Left Aortic Sinus</data>
      <data key="d1">location</data>
      <data key="d2">One of the three aortic sinuses located in the ascending aorta, giving rise to the left coronary artery.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-830f7c80bbd34b9d892fbd4d5954c36a</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776198947</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Right Aortic Sinus">
      <data key="d0">Right Aortic Sinus</data>
      <data key="d1">location</data>
      <data key="d2">One of the three aortic sinuses located in the ascending aorta, giving rise to the right coronary artery.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-830f7c80bbd34b9d892fbd4d5954c36a</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776198947</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Posterior Aortic Sinus">
      <data key="d0">Posterior Aortic Sinus</data>
      <data key="d1">location</data>
      <data key="d2">The posterior aortic sinus is known as the non-coronary sinus and usually contains no vessels.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-830f7c80bbd34b9d892fbd4d5954c36a</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776198947</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Left Coronary Artery">
      <data key="d0">Left Coronary Artery</data>
      <data key="d1">data</data>
      <data key="d2">The left coronary artery is a vessel that originates from the left aortic sinus.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-830f7c80bbd34b9d892fbd4d5954c36a</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776198947</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Non-Coronary Sinus">
      <data key="d0">Non-Coronary Sinus</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-830f7c80bbd34b9d892fbd4d5954c36a</data>
      <data key="d2">The non-coronary sinus is also known as the posterior aortic sinus due to its lack of connections to coronary arteries.</data>
      <data key="d1">UNKNOWN</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776198948</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Osteoporosis">
      <data key="d0">Osteoporosis</data>
      <data key="d1">condition</data>
      <data key="d2">Osteoporosis is a condition characterized by decreased bone mineral density and small pores in bones, leading to pathological fractures.&lt;SEP&gt;Osteoporosis is a bone-thinning condition that increases the risk of fractures and osteoporotic compression fractures.&lt;SEP&gt;Osteoporosis is a bone disorder that becomes weak and prone to fractures during menopause, largely attributed to estrogen deficiency.&lt;SEP&gt;Prolonged exposure to glucocorticoids can contribute to the development of osteoporosis in patients with adrenal insufficiency.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-dab5c45c4fc2e203d5776e4e9eb8385c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-40324022a0e3a72859b0d0b0a9c2b089&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e80dc7bcd1293375ca72b55372764fe1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a90bf38c850a0d10b54a8c7b210bf24c</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776236245</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Turner Biomechanics Laboratory">
      <data key="d0">Turner Biomechanics Laboratory</data>
      <data key="d1">organization</data>
      <data key="d2">The Turner Biomechanics Laboratory is the source of research on osteoporosis.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-dab5c45c4fc2e203d5776e4e9eb8385c</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776199086</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Bone Density">
      <data key="d0">Bone Density</data>
      <data key="d1">measurement</data>
      <data key="d2">Bone density is measured in terms of mineral content, specifically trabecular bone mineral density (BMD).</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-dab5c45c4fc2e203d5776e4e9eb8385c</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776199087</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Wikimedia.org">
      <data key="d0">Wikimedia.org</data>
      <data key="d1">organization</data>
      <data key="d2">The source of the research on osteoporosis conducted by Turner Biomechanics Laboratory.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-dab5c45c4fc2e203d5776e4e9eb8385c</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776199087</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Research Findings">
      <data key="d0">Research Findings</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-dab5c45c4fc2e203d5776e4e9eb8385c</data>
      <data key="d2">The Turner Biomechanics Laboratory conducted research on the gross pathology of osteoporotic bone.</data>
      <data key="d1">UNKNOWN</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776199087</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
