    <node id="Hyperosmolar Hyperglycemic State">
      <data key="d0">Hyperosmolar Hyperglycemic State</data>
      <data key="d1">data</data>
      <data key="d2">Hyperosmolar hyperglycemic state (HHS) is a serious complication of diabetes that occurs when the body's ability to regulate blood sugar levels is severely impaired.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-18b3a59bf7f5ccc18f7641e35b20249f</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776232341</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Old Age">
      <data key="d0">Old Age</data>
      <data key="d1">person</data>
      <data key="d2">Old age is one factor associated with an increased risk of developing hyperosmolar hyperglycemic state (HHS).</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-18b3a59bf7f5ccc18f7641e35b20249f</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776232341</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="High Mean Glycosylated Hemoglobin A1c">
      <data key="d0">High Mean Glycosylated Hemoglobin A1c</data>
      <data key="d1">data</data>
      <data key="d2">A high mean glycosylated hemoglobin A1c (HbA1c) level is associated with an increased risk of hyperosmolar hyperglycemic state (HHS).</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-18b3a59bf7f5ccc18f7641e35b20249f</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776232341</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Acromegaly">
      <data key="d0">Acromegaly</data>
      <data key="d1">physiologicalstressors</data>
      <data key="d2">Acromegaly is a condition characterized by excessive growth hormone secretion, which can lead to physiological stress and increase the risk of HHS.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-18b3a59bf7f5ccc18f7641e35b20249f</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776232341</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Cerebrovascular Accident">
      <data key="d0">Cerebrovascular Accident</data>
      <data key="d1">physiologicalstressors</data>
      <data key="d2">A stroke caused by a blockage or rupture of blood vessels in the brain can contribute to an increased risk of HHS.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-18b3a59bf7f5ccc18f7641e35b20249f</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776232341</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Cushing's Disease">
      <data key="d0">Cushing's Disease</data>
      <data key="d1">physiologicalstressors</data>
      <data key="d2">Cushing's disease, characterized by excess cortisol production, is another factor associated with an increased risk of developing hyperosmolar hyperglycemic state (HHS).</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-18b3a59bf7f5ccc18f7641e35b20249f</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776232341</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Hemochromatosis">
      <data key="d0">Hemochromatosis</data>
      <data key="d1">physiologicalstressors</data>
      <data key="d2">Iron overload due to hemochromatosis can increase the risk of HHS.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-18b3a59bf7f5ccc18f7641e35b20249f</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776232342</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Heatstroke">
      <data key="d0">Heatstroke</data>
      <data key="d1">physiologicalstressors</data>
      <data key="d2">Exposure to high temperatures can lead to heatstroke, increasing the risk of HHS.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-18b3a59bf7f5ccc18f7641e35b20249f</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776232342</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Hypothermia">
      <data key="d0">Hypothermia</data>
      <data key="d1">physiologicalstressors</data>
      <data key="d2">Abnormally low body temperature (hypothermia) is another factor associated with an increased risk of developing hyperosmolar hyperglycemic state (HHS).</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-18b3a59bf7f5ccc18f7641e35b20249f</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776232342</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Dialysis">
      <data key="d0">Dialysis</data>
      <data key="d1">data</data>
      <data key="d2">Patients undergoing dialysis are at a higher risk of developing hyperosmolar hyperglycemic state (HHS) due to the dialysis process itself and potential complications.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-18b3a59bf7f5ccc18f7641e35b20249f</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776232343</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Burns">
      <data key="d0">Burns</data>
      <data key="d1">physiologicalstressors</data>
      <data key="d2">Severe burns can lead to physiological stress, increasing the risk of HHS.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-18b3a59bf7f5ccc18f7641e35b20249f</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776232343</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Neuroleptic Malignant Syndrome">
      <data key="d0">Neuroleptic Malignant Syndrome</data>
      <data key="d1">physiologicalstressors</data>
      <data key="d2">This rare and potentially life-threatening condition is caused by an adverse reaction to neuroleptic medications, leading to increased risk of HHS.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-18b3a59bf7f5ccc18f7641e35b20249f</data>
