      <data key="d12">1776220306</data>
      <data key="d13" />
    </edge>
    <edge source="Debris" target="Stool Guaiac Test">
      <data key="d7">1.0</data>
      <data key="d8">The guaiac test is used to detect blood in stool by identifying debris that can be found when blood mixes with bile.</data>
      <data key="d9">analyzed component,substance</data>
      <data key="d10">chunk-8442ec3153c9dbbd0097bc0cb7253340</data>
      <data key="d11">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d12">1776220306</data>
      <data key="d13" />
    </edge>
    <edge source="Debris" target="Bile">
      <data key="d7">1.0</data>
      <data key="d8">Bile is a digestive fluid produced by the liver and stored in the gallbladder that can mix with blood to form debris.</data>
      <data key="d9">associated component,substance</data>
      <data key="d10">chunk-8442ec3153c9dbbd0097bc0cb7253340</data>
      <data key="d11">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d12">1776220308</data>
      <data key="d13" />
    </edge>
    <edge source="Anemia" target="Serum Iron Test">
      <data key="d7">1.0</data>
      <data key="d8">The serum iron test measures the level of iron in the blood to help diagnose anemia.</data>
      <data key="d9">condition assessment,diagnostic tool</data>
      <data key="d10">chunk-8442ec3153c9dbbd0097bc0cb7253340</data>
      <data key="d11">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d12">1776220308</data>
      <data key="d13" />
    </edge>
    <edge source="Anemia" target="Serum Ferritin Test">
      <data key="d7">1.0</data>
      <data key="d8">The serum ferritin test measures the level of iron stored in the body's tissues and fluids, which can help diagnose anemia.</data>
      <data key="d9">condition assessment,diagnostic tool</data>
      <data key="d10">chunk-8442ec3153c9dbbd0097bc0cb7253340</data>
      <data key="d11">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d12">1776220309</data>
      <data key="d13" />
    </edge>
    <edge source="Stool Guaiac Test" target="Blood">
      <data key="d7">1.0</data>
      <data key="d8">The guaiac test detects blood in stool by identifying the presence of heme, a protein found in red blood cells, which mixes with bile to form debris.</data>
      <data key="d9">analyzed component,substance</data>
      <data key="d10">chunk-8442ec3153c9dbbd0097bc0cb7253340</data>
      <data key="d11">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d12">1776220308</data>
      <data key="d13" />
    </edge>
    <edge source="Phyllodes Tumor" target="Sclerosing Adenosis">
      <data key="d7">2.0</data>
      <data key="d8">A comparison of Phyllodes tumors and Sclerosing adenosis reveals differences in their potential for malignancy, cellular abnormality, and clinical implications.&lt;SEP&gt;Sclerosing adenosis, although considered benign, carries a higher risk of breast cancer compared to Phyllodes tumors, which can be either benign or malignant.</data>
      <data key="d9">benign vs malignant,comparison and contrast</data>
      <data key="d10">chunk-4c4689566af7f5f15132f08d3ceb0561</data>
      <data key="d11">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d12">1776220392</data>
      <data key="d13" />
    </edge>
    <edge source="Phyllodes Tumor" target="ADH (Atypical Ductal Hyperplasia)">
      <data key="d7">2.0</data>
      <data key="d8">The clinical implications of Phyllodes tumors and ADH are distinct due to their varying degrees of cellular abnormality and risk for malignancy.&lt;SEP&gt;ADH, as a low-grade DCIS with localized proliferation, is considered an atypical condition due to the abnormal growth patterns of its cells.</data>
      <data key="d9">clinical significance</data>
      <data key="d10">chunk-4c4689566af7f5f15132f08d3ceb0561</data>
      <data key="d11">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d12">1776220393</data>
      <data key="d13" />
    </edge>
    <edge source="Phyllodes Tumor" target="Histopathologic Image (Source: Nephron, from Wikimedia Commons)">
      <data key="d7">3.0</data>
      <data key="d8">The histopathologic image of Phyllodes tumor provides insight into its molecular basis, which aids in understanding its clinical significance.&lt;SEP&gt;The histopathologic image of Phyllodes tumor helps in characterizing its type and determining its potential for malignancy.&lt;SEP&gt;The histopathologic image is sourced from Nephron and Wikimedia Commons for Phyllodes tumor characterization.</data>
      <data key="d9">imaging source,molecular basis,tumor characterization</data>
      <data key="d10">chunk-4c4689566af7f5f15132f08d3ceb0561</data>
      <data key="d11">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d12">1776220394</data>
      <data key="d13" />
    </edge>
    <edge source="Sclerosing Adenosis" target="ADH (Atypical Ductal Hyperplasia)">
      <data key="d7">5.0</data>
      <data key="d8">Both conditions carry increased risks for breast cancer, with Sclerosing adenosis being considered a benign lesion and ADH displaying abnormal growth patterns.&lt;SEP&gt;Both conditions carry increased risks for breast cancer, with Sclerosing adenosis being considered benign and ADH displaying abnormal growth patterns.&lt;SEP&gt;Both conditions carry increased risks for breast cancer, with ADH having a higher grade of abnormality in its cellular growth patterns.&lt;SEP&gt;Both conditions share an increased risk for breast cancer, but their underlying pathological characteristics differ significantly.&lt;SEP&gt;Both sclerosing adenosis and ADH carry increased risks for breast cancer, but the nature of their cellular abnormalities differs.</data>
      <data key="d9">comparative risk assessment</data>
      <data key="d10">chunk-4c4689566af7f5f15132f08d3ceb0561</data>
      <data key="d11">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d12">1776220393</data>
      <data key="d13" />
    </edge>
    <edge source="Sclerosing Adenosis" target="Histopathologic Image (Source: Nephron, from Wikimedia Commons)">
      <data key="d7">2.0</data>
      <data key="d8">The histopathologic image of sclerosing adenosis is sourced from Nephron and Wikimedia Commons for its identification as a benign lesion.&lt;SEP&gt;The microscopic pathology of sclerosing adenosis aids in identifying it as a benign lesion with increased risk of breast cancer.</data>
      <data key="d9">benign lesion identification,imaging source</data>
      <data key="d10">chunk-4c4689566af7f5f15132f08d3ceb0561</data>
      <data key="d11">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d12">1776220396</data>
      <data key="d13" />
    </edge>
    <edge source="ADH (Atypical Ductal Hyperplasia)" target="Histopathologic Image (Source: Nephron, from Wikimedia Commons)">
      <data key="d7">5.0</data>
      <data key="d8">The histopathologic image of ADH highlights its pathological characteristics, including localized proliferation and abnormal cell growth patterns.&lt;SEP&gt;The histopathologic image of ADH is sourced from Nephron and Wikimedia Commons for its clinical diagnosis based on molecular basis.&lt;SEP&gt;The histopathologic image of ADH is crucial for making an accurate clinical diagnosis based on its molecular basis.&lt;SEP&gt;The histopathologic image of ADH is essential for making a diagnosis based on its molecular characteristics.&lt;SEP&gt;The histopathologic image provides critical information for assessing the molecular basis of risk in ADH.</data>
      <data key="d9">clinical diagnosis,imaging source,molecular basis,molecular basis of risk assessment,pathological characteristics</data>
      <data key="d10">chunk-4c4689566af7f5f15132f08d3ceb0561</data>
